\title{Cyton Dongle}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Connect and stream from OpenBCI Cyton/Daisy via USB dongle, including first-time radio channel pairing}

\subtree{
\title{Cyton Dongle}
\p{USB wireless receiver (RFD22301/RFDuino) for OpenBCI Cyton 8/16-channel EEG board.}

\subtree{
\title{Hardware}
\ul{
\li{\strong{Dongle}: FTDI FT231X USB-UART → RFDuino 2.4 GHz radio}
\li{\strong{Serial}: 115200 baud, 8N1}
\li{\strong{Device}: \code{\startverb /dev/cu.usbserial-*\stopverb} (macOS) or \code{\startverb /dev/ttyUSB*\stopverb} (Linux)}
\li{\strong{Sample Rate}: 250 Hz}
\li{\strong{Channels}: 8 (Cyton) or 16 (Cyton + Daisy)}
\li{\strong{Packet}: 33 bytes (0xA0 start, 24 bytes channel data, 6 bytes aux, 1 byte counter, 0xC0 stop)}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{First-Time Pairing (Critical)}
\p{A new dongle and board are typically on \strong{different radio channels}. The standard \code{\startverb 0xF0 0x01\stopverb} channel-set command requires both sides to handshake — it \strong{fails when they're on different channels}.}

\p{Use \code{\startverb 0xF0 0x02\stopverb} (CHANNEL_SET_OVERRIDE) to force the dongle to each channel without requiring board response, then check system status:}

\pre{\startverb
import serial, time

ser = serial.Serial('/dev/cu.usbserial-XXXXX', 115200, timeout=2)
time.sleep(2)

for chan in range(26):
    ser.reset_input_buffer()
    ser.write(bytes([0xF0, 0x02, chan]))  # override dongle (no handshake)
    time.sleep(0.5)
    ser.read(ser.in_waiting or 512)

    ser.reset_input_buffer()
    ser.write(bytes([0xF0, 0x07]))        # system status query
    time.sleep(0.5)
    resp = ser.read(ser.in_waiting or 512).decode('utf-8', errors='ignore')

    if 'System is Up' in resp:
        print(f'FOUND BOARD ON CHANNEL {chan}')
        break
    else:
        print(f'Ch {chan}: Down')

ser.close()
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Radio Commands (0xF0 prefix)}
\pre{\startverb
| Bytes | Command | Notes |
|-------|---------|-------|
| `0xF0 0x00` | CHANNEL_GET | Returns current dongle channel |
| `0xF0 0x01 <ch>` | CHANNEL_SET | Coordinated change, **requires board online** |
| `0xF0 0x02 <ch>` | CHANNEL_OVERRIDE | **Dongle-only, no handshake** — use for pairing |
| `0xF0 0x03` | POLL_TIME_GET | Current poll time |
| `0xF0 0x04 <t>` | POLL_TIME_SET | Set poll time |
| `0xF0 0x05` | BAUD_DEFAULT | 115200 |
| `0xF0 0x06` | BAUD_FAST | 230400 |
| `0xF0 0x07` | SYS_STATUS | "System is Up" or "System is Down" |
| `0xF0 0x0A` | BAUD_HYPER | 921600 |
\stopverb}

\p{Channels are 0-25. Default for new boards is usually 1.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Serial Commands}
\pre{\startverb
| Cmd | Action |
|-----|--------|
| `v` | Firmware version + board info |
| `b` | Start binary streaming |
| `s` | Stop streaming |
| `C` | Enable Daisy (16ch mode) |
| `D` | Query Daisy module |
| `?` | Print ADS1299 registers |
| `1`-`8` | Default channel settings (ch 1-8) |
| `!`-`*` | Default channel settings (ch 9-16, Daisy) |
| `d` | Reset all channel defaults |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Parsing Binary Packets}
\pre{\startverb
SCALE_UV = 4.5 / (24 * (2**23 - 1)) * 1e6  # ~0.02235 uV/count

def parse_24bit(b0, b1, b2):
    val = (b0 << 16) | (b1 << 8) | b2
    return val - 0x1000000 if val >= 0x800000 else val
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{33-byte packet}: \code{\startverb 0xA0 | sample_num | 8×3-byte channels | 6-byte aux | 0xC0\stopverb}}

\p{With Daisy: odd sample numbers = channels 1-8, even = channels 9-16.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Streaming and Channel Quality Check}
\pre{\startverb
import serial, time, math

ser = serial.Serial('/dev/cu.usbserial-XXXXX', 115200, timeout=5)
time.sleep(2)
ser.reset_input_buffer()

# Override to known channel
ser.write(bytes([0xF0, 0x02, CHANNEL]))
time.sleep(1)
ser.read(ser.in_waiting or 512)

# Reset board
ser.write(b'v')
time.sleep(3)
ser.read(ser.in_waiting or 4096)
ser.reset_input_buffer()

SCALE_UV = 4.5 / (24 * (2**23 - 1)) * 1e6

def p24(b0, b1, b2):
    v = (b0 << 16) | (b1 << 8) | b2
    return v - 0x1000000 if v >= 0x800000 else v

# Start stream
ser.write(b'b')
time.sleep(1.5)
ser.read(ser.in_waiting or 2048)  # drain text

samples = {i: [] for i in range(16)}
t0 = time.time()

while (time.time() - t0) < 4:
    avail = ser.in_waiting
    if not avail:
        time.sleep(0.01)
        continue
    buf = ser.read(avail)
    i = 0
    while i < len(buf) - 32:
        if buf[i] == 0xA0 and buf[i+32] == 0xC0:
            sn = buf[i+1]
            is_daisy = (sn % 2 == 0)
            for ch in range(8):
                off = i + 2 + ch * 3
                raw = p24(buf[off], buf[off+1], buf[off+2])
                samples[ch + (8 if is_daisy else 0)].append(raw * SCALE_UV)
            i += 33
        else:
            i += 1

ser.write(b's')
ser.close()

# Assess quality
for ch in range(16):
    vals = samples[ch]
    if len(vals) < 10:
        print(f'Ch {ch+1}: NO DATA')
        continue
    mean = sum(vals) / len(vals)
    std = math.sqrt(sum((v - mean)**2 for v in vals) / len(vals))
    if abs(mean) > 187000: q = 'RAILED'
    elif std < 1:          q = 'FLAT'
    elif std > 200:        q = 'BAD CONTACT'
    elif std > 100:        q = 'NOISY'
    elif std < 50:         q = 'CLEAN'
    else:                  q = 'OK'
    print(f'Ch {ch+1}: {q} (std={std:.1f} uV)')
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Ultracortex Mark IV 16ch Montage (10-20)}
\pre{\startverb
| Ch | Position | Ch | Position |
|----|----------|----|----------|
| 1 | Fp1 | 9 | F7 |
| 2 | Fp2 | 10 | F8 |
| 3 | C3 | 11 | F3 |
| 4 | C4 | 12 | F4 |
| 5 | P7 | 13 | T7 |
| 6 | P8 | 14 | T8 |
| 7 | O1 | 15 | P3 |
| 8 | O2 | 16 | P4 |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Daisy Module (16ch)}
\p{The Daisy stacks on top of the Cyton, adding a second ADS1299 for channels 9-16.}

\p{\strong{Verifying Daisy}:}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb v\stopverb} should report: \code{\startverb On Daisy ADS1299 Device ID: 0x3E\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb D\stopverb} returns Daisy firmware version (e.g., \code{\startverb 060110\stopverb})}
\li{\code{\startverb C\stopverb} enables 16ch mode, returns \code{\startverb 16\stopverb}}
\li{\code{\startverb c\stopverb} (lowercase) disables Daisy, returns \code{\startverb daisy removed\stopverb}}
}

\p{\strong{Daisy interleaving}: In 16ch mode, the board alternates packets:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{Odd sample numbers} (1,3,5...): channels 1-8 (main board)}
\li{\strong{Even sample numbers} (2,4,6...): channels 9-16 (Daisy)}
}

\p{Expect ~1:1 ratio of main:daisy packets. If Daisy packets are missing or all-zero, check that the Daisy board is firmly seated on the Cyton header pins.}
}

\subtree{
\title{ADS1299 Registers}
\p{Query with \code{\startverb ?\stopverb}. Key registers per channel:}

\pre{\startverb
| Register | Default | Meaning |
|----------|---------|---------|
| `0x68` | Normal input, gain 24x, powered on |
| `0xE8` | Powered down (bit 7 set) |
| `0x60` | Normal input, gain 24x, SRB2 off |
\stopverb}

\ul{
\li{\code{\startverb BIAS_SENSP = 0xFF\stopverb}: All channels feeding bias drive (good)}
\li{\code{\startverb CONFIG1 = 0xB6\stopverb}: 250 Hz sample rate, daisy mode}
\li{\code{\startverb CONFIG3 = 0xEC\stopverb}: Internal reference, bias enabled}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Electrode Quality Thresholds}
\pre{\startverb
| Std Dev (uV) | Status | Meaning |
|--------------|--------|---------|
| < 1 | FLAT | Shorted to reference or no contact |
| < 50 | CLEAN | Good signal, usable for all analysis |
| 50-100 | OK | Usable for most band power analysis |
| 100-200 | NOISY | May work for gross features (eye blinks) |
| > 200 | BAD CONTACT | Electrode touching but loose |
| mean ±187500 | RAILED | Not touching skin, pinned to ADC rail |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Session Persistence}
\p{The dongle \strong{does not persist} the channel override across serial sessions. Every time you open a new serial connection, you must re-send \code{\startverb 0xF0 0x02 <channel>\stopverb}. Keep the serial port open for the duration of your recording, or store the known channel and re-override on connect.}

\p{The board also goes to \strong{sleep after extended idle} with no streaming. Toggle the power switch OFF→PC to wake it, then re-scan.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Dongle Switch Position}
\p{The dongle has a small switch with two positions:}

\pre{\startverb
| Position | Mode | Use |
|----------|------|-----|
| **GPIO_6** | Normal operation | **Use this for data streaming** |
| **Reset** | Bootloader/programming | Firmware upload only |
\stopverb}

\p{If the switch is on "Reset", commands may partially work (radio config, \code{\startverb v\stopverb}, \code{\startverb ?\stopverb}) but \strong{binary streaming will fail} — the RFDuino stays in bootloader mode and cannot relay continuous data. This is easy to miss because single-shot commands still get responses.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\pre{\startverb
| Symptom | Cause | Fix |
|---------|-------|-----|
| "Device failed to poll Host" | Channel mismatch | Use `0xF0 0x02` override scan (see above) |
| "System is Down" | Board off or wrong channel | Check power, scan channels |
| Channel stuck on set | `0x01` needs board handshake | Use `0x02` override instead |
| RAILED at ±187500 uV | Electrode not connected | Check pin seating and wire |
| FLAT near 0 | Shorted to ref or no contact | Apply gel, press electrode |
| FLAT at exactly 0.0 | Daisy wires not plugged in | Check header pin connections |
| High noise (>200 uV std) | Poor electrode contact | Tighten cap, add paste |
| 0 packets after `b` | Dongle switch on "Reset" | Set switch to **GPIO_6** position |
| Commands work, stream doesn't | Dongle in bootloader mode | Check switch is GPIO_6, not Reset |
| Daisy ch all zero | Daisy not seated or `C` not sent | Reseat Daisy, send `C` before `b` |
| All channels railed one side | Cap too loose / wrong size | Tighten straps, try gel electrodes |
| Commands work but stream doesn't | Board slept during idle | Toggle OFF→PC, re-pair |
\stopverb}
}

